# [The Diagnostic Process](#contents.html_chapter02-1){#chapter02.html_chapter02} {.chaptitle}

After hearing the school psychologist's concerns about ASD, Lauren's parents began reading everything they could get their hands on about the condition. The label seemed to fit Lauren well in some ways, particularly concerning her lack of friends and trouble looking people in the eye, but other features, like overly formal language and clumsiness, just didn't sound like their daughter. The school psychologist felt pretty strongly that a diagnosis of ASD explained Lauren's challenges and would help her obtain needed services, but suggested they get a second opinion, recommending an experienced local child psychiatrist. At the request of the psychiatrist, Lauren's parents obtained copies of her medical records from their pediatrician. In a report dictated after Lauren's 3-year check-up, they read, "This young girl, born prematurely, is now thriving. She is physically well developed, alert, and happy, although she is described by her parents as quite shy and fearful. We spent some time assessing development. She played alone throughout the visit and rarely looked up at the adults. She was having difficulty focusing on tasks.... Lauren clearly has some interaction difficulties, though her relatedness is probably okay for her age." Lauren's parents were startled that the doctor had noted, way back then, their daughter's solitariness, and were both confused and frustrated by the conclusion. Why hadn't this been figured out sooner?

[]{#chapter02.html_page_23}At age 2, Seth was not yet talking and seemed indifferent to his siblings and parents. When people called his name or spoke to him, he didn't appear to hear them. His parents were sure he wasn't deaf, as he would perk up whenever the automatic garage door opened, even when he was in distant parts of the house. But just to be on the safe side, Seth's parents had his hearing tested. The results were perfectly normal, but the audiologist asked them if they had ever considered autism. This diagnosis was confirmed by a child psychologist at age 3. Seth was immediately enrolled in a special education preschool for children with autism. He began talking quickly and made rapid progress in all areas, such that he was able to enter kindergarten in a regular classroom with just some minimal assistance from an aide. As he began school, his parents were told that he did not have autism, but actually something called Asperger syndrome. Several years later, a psychologist working with Seth mentioned "big changes" in the diagnostic system to his parents and said he now met criteria for ASD. Who was right and why did the labels keep changing?

There are many routes through the maze of diagnosis, some direct, others taking trips down blind alleys and leading to dead ends. In this chapter, we help you find your way by explaining the specific diagnostic criteria for ASD and related conditions. We'll tell you how a diagnostic evaluation is conducted and how diagnostic decisions about your child should be made; we will also discuss conditions sometimes confused with ASD.

**THE DIAGNOSTIC BIBLE: THE DSM**

The diagnostic process varies from agency to agency and from professional to professional. Some evaluations are comprehensive and lengthy, others relatively quick. Some professionals will use special tests, while others will talk with you and play with your child in a seemingly informal manner. But all will be collecting []{#chapter02.html_page_24}specific information about your child's early development and current strengths and weaknesses in the areas relevant to ASD. As we outlined in [Chapter 1](#chapter01.html), these areas are your child's social interaction and communication skills, as well as any special interests or unusual behaviors. Once this information is collected, a decision is made about whether your child meets criteria for ASD. To do this, professionals use the American Psychiatric Association's *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* (or DSM), which outlines the specific behaviors and problems associated with all emotional, behavioral, and mental conditions. The DSM is currently in its fifth edition, known as DSM-5, which was published in May 2013. The DSM is revised every decade or two to reflect new knowledge amassed by clinicians and researchers in mental health. If your child was diagnosed some time ago, then an earlier edition may have been used, probably the DSM-IV (the fourth edition), which came out in 1994 and was used until 2013. If you live outside the United States, the manual called the *International Classification of Diseases* (or ICD) may have been used instead.

As Seth's parents heard, major changes occurred in the way we think about and diagnose ASD between the fourth and fifth editions of the DSM. Many people were initially upset about the changes and didn't understand why they were made. Parents worried that their child would lose his diagnosis and no longer be able to access services that had been helpful. Before we tell you about the current system, DSM-5, we'll provide some information about DSM-IV and why these big changes were made, so you can understand the debate and how this might affect your child.

**DSM-IV**

In DSM-IV, the category that contained the autism spectrum disorders was called "pervasive developmental disorders." This umbrella term was used by the authors of the DSM to differentiate []{#chapter02.html_page_25}autism spectrum conditions from more specific developmental disorders, like learning disabilities. Children with pervasive developmental disorders experienced difficulty across multiple (or "pervasive") areas of development (social, communication, behavior, cognition, sometimes even motor skills). In contrast, children with specific developmental disorders, like dyslexia, had problems in only one specific area (such as reading) but functioned well in other areas, like social and motor skills.

There were five specific conditions included within the pervasive developmental disorder, or PDD, category in DSM-IV: autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, Rett's disorder, childhood disintegrative disorder, and pervasive developmental disorder not otherwise specified (PDD-NOS). Two of the conditions, namely Rett's disorder and childhood disintegrative disorder, are always associated with significant cognitive impairment and are not considered on the high-functioning part of the autism spectrum, so we will not say more about them in this book. The other three DSM-IV conditions, autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, and PDD-NOS, all shared difficulties with social interaction, communication, and repetitive behaviors but differed in the specific number and pattern of symptoms. Children with autistic disorder (the DSM-IV term for autism) had to demonstrate at least six difficulties (or symptoms) in social interaction, communication, and repetitive behaviors from a list of 12. "High-functioning autism" was the term used for individuals who met autistic disorder criteria and had relatively normal thinking, learning, and language skills. Children with Asperger's disorder (the DSM-IV term for Asperger syndrome) showed fewer than six symptoms and, in addition, had to have typical levels of language, not only at the time of assessment, but throughout their lives---that is, no late talkers in this category. Finally, the DSM-IV diagnosis of PDD-NOS was used for children who did not meet the full criteria for either autistic disorder or Asperger's disorder, usually because they had either too few symptoms or the wrong pattern of symptoms. For example, if a child displayed four symptoms (too few for autistic disorder) and []{#chapter02.html_page_26}had delayed language (ruling out Asperger's disorder), the diagnosis of PDD-NOS would have been used according to DSM-IV.

**NEW RESEARCH BRINGS MAJOR CHANGES TO THE DSM**

The main reason the DSM, now in its fifth edition, keeps changing is that doctors want the diagnostic system to keep pace with the rapidly expanding knowledge that comes from ongoing scientific research. The first edition of the DSM was published in 1952 and did not include autism or anything like it; neither did the second edition, published in
1968. Children with autistic-type behaviors were labeled with
"schizophrenia, childhood type," if they got a diagnosis at all. Autism was not added to the DSM until the third edition, in 1980. This was because research done in the 1970s clearly showed that autism was different from childhood schizophrenia. At the time, this rearranging of the diagnostic criteria was just as major as the current changes. But imagine if the DSM had not been revised and we were still using criteria based on science from 60 years ago---no one with ASD would even have a diagnosis! So you can see why updates to the DSM, based on new research, can be very helpful.

What were the recent scientific findings that led to DSM-5? Ever since Dr. Lorna Wing brought Asperger syndrome to the attention of the English-speaking world in the 1980s, researchers and clinicians noticed the similarities to high-functioning autism and wondered how the two conditions differed. Several differences were proposed: for example, maybe children with Asperger syndrome were clumsier than those with autism; some researchers and clinicians thought that children with Asperger syndrome were more likely to have special interests (like memorizing facts about the French Revolution) than children with autism; or maybe those with Asperger syndrome were more likely to talk in a formal way (like a "little professor") than children with high-functioning []{#chapter02.html_page_27}autism. Over the last two decades, dozens of studies have been conducted to examine these hypotheses, and many others, about what distinguishes autism from Asperger syndrome. These investigations found very few differences between the two conditions---or none at all. It seemed that the only distinctions between high-functioning autism and Asperger syndrome were the number of symptoms (more or fewer than six) and language development at ages 2 and 3 (delayed or not). Most professionals would agree that these are small differences. Observing a group of teenagers, some of whom were diagnosed with Asperger syndrome and others of whom were diagnosed with high-functioning autism, both parents and professionals were hard-pressed to know which child had which condition. This led to a very common but unfortunate experience for many families, who received different diagnostic opinions from different doctors, with one professional diagnosing their child with Asperger syndrome and another telling them that it was actually high-functioning autism (or, like Seth, changing from one diagnosis to the other as the child got older).

An eye-opening study conducted in 2012 by Dr. Catherine Lord and a group of clinical researchers from across the United States showed how differently the diagnoses of autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, and PDD-NOS were used at different centers. At some clinics, virtually all children were diagnosed with autistic disorder and the other two labels were rarely used. At others, PDD-NOS was the most common, and at still other centers Asperger's disorder made up half of the sample. Were there really such drastically different rates of the three conditions in different parts of the country? In fact, the study showed clearly that children at the different sites were quite similar: they had similar levels of language, intelligence, and severity of autistic behaviors. So it was nothing in the children that was leading to these vastly different rates of autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, and PDD-NOS across the country. What differed from one center to another was how the clinicians *applied* the labels, with some centers seemingly more comfortable using certain diagnoses than others. This situation []{#chapter02.html_page_28}probably occurred all over the world (not just at the sites participating in this study) for the 20 years that DSM-IV was in use.

Not only was this confusing for families, but also it often had negative consequences for their child's care. In some parts of the United States and other countries, individuals with Asperger diagnoses were eligible for far fewer services than individuals with autism. So, if these are one and the same condition and children with both diagnoses share the same disabilities, it is obviously very unfair to deny services to some while providing a full range of interventions to others. Professionals hope that DSM-5 will address these inequities.

**DSM-5**

In response to the challenges raised by new research evidence and the problems with use of the labels we just described, DSM-5 was developed. This was a 4-year process that involved scientists and clinicians from many fields, as well as advocates from parent and community organizations. This group met regularly to discuss changes suggested by new research, develop new criteria, and then examine data to see how well the new diagnostic rules worked. The work group was given the instruction to "do no harm"---for each and every change, to make sure that it would not make things worse for patients and families, such as resulting in fewer people being eligible for a diagnosis or for services. DSM-5 was published in May 2013 and is now in widespread use throughout the United States and other parts of the world. While it is still too early to know all the effects that the changes may have on children and families, there are a few published studies that suggest it is doing a good job; we'll come back to this topic later, after telling you exactly what the DSM-5 criteria are.

In DSM-5, children like yours fall into the diagnosis of autism spectrum disorder (ASD). Unlike DSM-IV, which had a category called pervasive developmental disorders and five specific diagnoses []{#chapter02.html_page_29}within it, DSM-5 uses a single diagnosis, ASD. DSM-IV listed 12 symptoms and required different patterns to be met for the five different PDD diagnoses; this resulted in 2,688 different ways that an individual could meet criteria! This meant that there was tremendous variability among children and it was possible for two individuals with the same diagnosis not to share a single symptom. In DSM-5, the list of symptoms has been streamlined to seven and an individual must display at least five of them to receive an ASD diagnosis. In contrast to DSM-IV, there are only six different patterns a child may show. This will make the diagnostic process much more straightforward for clinicians and will increase reliability: since there is now just a single diagnostic label, it is much more likely that a child will receive the same diagnosis from two different practitioners than it was in DSM-IV. Families will not have to face the questions that Seth's parents did, wondering why one doctor said autism and the other Asperger syndrome.

In order to meet DSM-5 criteria for ASD, a child must show difficulties in social communication and interaction, as well as restricted, repetitive behaviors. In the social domain, there are three symptoms included in DSM-5: (1) difficulty in social reciprocity, such as engaging or conversing with others or sharing their feelings; (2) difficulty using nonverbal communication, such as eye contact, facial expressions, and gestures; and (3) difficulty developing relationships appropriate for that age level. In the restricted and repetitive behaviors area, DSM-5 includes four symptoms: (1) repetitive, unusual movements, use of objects, or speech; (2) unreasonable insistence on sameness and following familiar routines; (3) interests that are narrow in focus, overly intense, and/or unusual; and (4) over- or underreactivity to sensory experiences. More detailed descriptions of these behaviors are provided in [Chapter 1](#chapter01.html). Most of the symptoms are very similar to those in DSM-IV, but one new symptom was added. Sensory issues and sensitivities were not included in DSM-IV, but research studies demonstrated that they are very common in children on the spectrum, so they were added to DSM-5.

[]{#chapter02.html_page_30}To meet criteria for ASD, your child must display at least five of the seven symptoms listed in DSM-5---all three of those in the social interaction area and at least two of the four in the restricted/repetitive behaviors area. There are many different ways that each symptom can be displayed. For example, in the area of social reciprocity, one child may have challenges in back-and-forth conversation, while another child may ignore and avoid other people; both show problems with social reciprocity, but the manifestations of this symptom are different depending upon how affected the child is. This is a new innovation of DSM-5, in which the authors made each symptom applicable to all individuals on the spectrum, from toddlers to adults, from fluently verbal to nonverbal, from mildly to severely affected. In contrast to DSM-IV, symptoms are phrased as "deficits in" rather than "lack of" a particular behavior, making them more applicable to a high-functioning child. As clinicians switched from DSM-IV to DSM-5, they have been surprised that, contrary to their expectations, it is in many cases easier for a child to meet criteria for a diagnosis, not harder.

An additional requirement for an ASD diagnosis is that symptoms must have been present in the early developmental period. No specific age of onset is given, but it is likely that most parents will be aware of at least some of these differences in their child before the age of 5. Occasionally parents may not notice problems until their child starts school, when the social demands and expectations for behavior become much higher and differences from other children become more evident. If your child fulfills these criteria (number of symptoms, pattern of symptoms across the two domains, and when differences were first apparent), then he or she will be diagnosed with ASD.

As part of the diagnostic process, your child's doctor will also specify whether he has any intellectual impairment (lowered cognitive and learning skills), language impairment, or genetic disorder (for example, Down syndrome or fragile X syndrome), along with ASD. A full diagnostic work-up will also make sure that your child doesn't have any additional diagnoses, like depression []{#chapter02.html_page_31}or anxiety disorder---we will offer more on this topic later in this chapter. Finally, your doctor will make a rating of how severe your child's impairment is and what level of support she needs (the ratings given are: Level 1 "requiring support," Level 2 "requiring substantial support," and Level 3 "requiring very substantial support"). Most children with higher-functioning ASD, who have fluent language and pretty typical levels of learning and thinking skills, will be at Severity Level 1 or 2. Severity levels may decrease as the child gets older. DSM-5 states very carefully that severity categories "should not be used to determine eligibility for and provision of services" (page 51).

**HOW WILL DSM-5 AFFECT US?**

With the introduction of DSM-5, parents have had many concerns, particularly about whether their child will still meet criteria for a diagnosis and will continue to be eligible for government-supported therapies, educational services, or insurance coverage. One very important thing for you to know is that the educational system and the medical system can be quite different in many states and countries. Regional departments of education often have their own definitions of disability and their own criteria for who is eligible for special education services that are different from the medical community, where the DSM is used. So, if you live in a region where eligibility for special education is not based on DSM criteria, your child's services at school will not be affected by the changes in the DSM.

Even if your state or country does rely on DSM criteria to make decisions about special education eligibility, your school services should not be adversely affected by the new criteria. As we mentioned earlier, the goal of the DSM-5 work group was to "do no harm." The intent of the new criteria was to identify the same individuals who had met criteria in previous DSM versions. In fact, DSM-5 includes a very specific statement that "individuals with a []{#chapter02.html_page_32}well-established DSM-IV diagnosis of autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, or pervasive developmental disorder not otherwise specified should be given the diagnosis of autism spectrum disorder" (page 51). This not only implies that your child will continue to meet criteria under DSM-5 if he did under DSM-IV but also suggests that your child does not need to get rediagnosed---that the new diagnostic label of ASD will now simply be used in place of your child's old diagnostic label. So, unless your doctor or school system tells you something different, you do not need to schedule a new assessment to make sure your child still meets criteria---you can presume that he will, unless otherwise notified.

In some situations, however, a reevaluation may be necessary and a child may actually fail to meet the criteria. Why might this happen? In DSM-IV, a diagnosis of PDD-NOS required only two symptoms, one of which had to be in the social domain. There was no requirement that the child demonstrate any repetitive behaviors, while in DSM-5, a child must display at least two.

Chad was a late talker; now, at age 9, his language has improved a lot, but he still has trouble with conversations and looking people in the eye. However, he doesn't show any other clear symptoms of ASD. He has a few close friends, is highly imaginative, and has never had any unusually focused interests or other odd or repetitive behaviors.

In DSM-IV, Chad was diagnosed with PDD-NOS because he showed some difficulties associated with the autism spectrum but didn't demonstrate either the number or pattern of symptoms required for diagnoses of high-functioning autism or Asperger syndrome. These conditions required at least two deficits in reciprocal social interaction, but Chad showed only one (difficulty with eye contact). He also demonstrated a total of only three symptoms, while at least six were required for a DSM-IV autistic disorder diagnosis.

When DSM-5 was published, Chad's parents were told by a well-meaning (but mistaken) family member that they []{#chapter02.html_page_33}"better get him rediagnosed." They were shocked to hear that Chad did not meet criteria for ASD. The psychologist told them that there was a new diagnostic category, called social (pragmatic) communication disorder, which seemed to better explain Chad's difficulties. She explained that children with ASD are far more repetitive and stereotyped in their behavior than Chad---his challenges were in the use of language for social purposes, such as taking turns in conversation, taking the perspective of other people when talking, and understanding ambiguous language. All of these sounded very familiar to Chad's parents. In fact, it was often hard to follow him when he was trying to tell them about his day. He often wasn't clear and didn't give enough background so that they could follow what he was saying. One day, for example, he came home from school upset, saying repeatedly, "She was so mean today," without saying who "she" was. Was it his teacher? Another child in the class? The bus driver? What exactly had "she" done? His parents needed to ask a lot of questions before they could follow his story. Chad also seemed very literal to his parents. He often did not get jokes or metaphors, and they had learned not to say things that they didn't really mean (as in sarcasm or irony). The psychologist mentioned that one treatment for these kinds of problems, called pragmatic language therapy, was offered by some speech--language therapists in the area and gave them several referrals.

The symptoms of social (pragmatic) communication disorder include persistent challenges in using verbal and nonverbal communication in a social context, as manifested by difficulties in all four of the following: (1) using communication for social purposes, (2) changing communication to fit the context or adapt to the needs of the partner, (3) following rules of conversation and narrative, and (4) using and understanding nonliteral language (humor, metaphors, sarcasm). As you can see, they do overlap with ASD---in fact, most children with ASD will display many of these symptoms. However, if a child meets criteria for ASD, social (pragmatic) communication []{#chapter02.html_page_34}disorder is ruled out. In Chad's case, if he had displayed repetitive behaviors, in addition to his social-communication problems, he would have been diagnosed with ASD instead.

Whenever a new diagnosis is incorporated into the DSM, further study is required to determine whether it is a helpful addition. When Asperger syndrome was first included in DSM-IV, it initially seemed like it would be a useful way to identify previously undiagnosed children. It was only after research accrued over two decades that the problems with the label became clear---that it wasn't really any different from autism in its symptoms, seemed to have the same causes, and needed the same treatments. Over the next decade, the same kind of research will need to be conducted on social (pragmatic) communication disorder to make sure that it is truly different from ASD in symptoms, causes, and treatments and that, as with Asperger syndrome, we aren't just using two different names for the same thing again.

**DSM-5: A HELPFUL REVISION?**

It is still early to know how many children will lose their diagnosis from DSM-IV to DSM-5, but based on some early research we are hopeful that it won't be too many and that, when it does happen, children will meet criteria for other disorders that better fit their strengths, challenges, and treatment needs. Before each new version of the DSM is published, "field trials" are conducted to test how well the new criteria work when they are used in the community by local clinicians (not just by the kinds of experts who would be on the DSM work group). Different studies use different methods to test the new criteria. One of the most stringent ways to look at whether they are working as well as or better than the old criteria is for two clinicians to independently evaluate the same child, one using DSM-IV and the other using DSM-5. In a field trial, this process is repeated on many different children, with many different kinds of problems and diagnoses, at many different []{#chapter02.html_page_35}clinics and locations around the country, using many different clinicians. Then the field trial study calculates how often the two clinicians, using the two different versions of the DSM, agree that the child is on the autism spectrum. For example, what percentage of the children evaluated met criteria for autistic disorder, Asperger's disorder, or PDD-NOS in DSM-IV and also met criteria for ASD in DSM-5?

One large field trial was conducted prior to publication of DSM-5 using these methods. Overall, 89% of the diagnoses were in agreement across DSM-IV and DSM-5. Even more reassuring was that the number of diagnoses on the spectrum was actually higher in DSM-5 than in DSM-IV. That means that some of the disagreements between the two DSM versions came about because a child failed to meet criteria on DSM-IV but actually did meet criteria on DSM-5. This surprised many people and is good news for everyone who wants to ensure that children getting services under DSM-IV don't lose the rights to those services under DSM-5. Another recent study, done by Dr. Carla Mazefsky and her colleagues at the University of Pittsburgh, was conducted on adults with normal intelligence, a group who many people were concerned would be underdiagnosed by DSM-5. This study found that 93% of these mildly affected individuals met both DSM-IV and DSM-5 criteria.

There are other types of studies that are sometimes cited on the Internet or in the media, suggesting that DSM-5 will diagnose many fewer children than DSM-IV. None of these studies used the most stringent methods we just described for field trials, so the lower rates they found may be due to using less strict research techniques. Some people are concerned that the new criteria will be hard to use with toddlers and very young children who may be on the autism spectrum, and research teams are actively studying this question. As more time elapses since the first implementation of DSM-5, more studies will be conducted and we will have a more definite answer about how well DSM-5 is doing, but we are optimistic at this point based on the first published field trials.

[]{#chapter02.html_page_36}As you have just read, there are many different ways that a particular symptom might be evident. This means that you may read accounts of ASD that do not sound like your child. You may know a neighborhood boy with ASD who seems quite different from your son. You may have heard that all children with ASD are unaffectionate, but your child loves hugs, kisses, and cuddles on your lap. Thus it is likely that some things about the diagnosis fit your child while others do not, as Lauren's parents experienced; this does not necessarily indicate that your child was diagnosed incorrectly. But how do you know?

**IS THE DIAGNOSIS ACCURATE?**

After reading the last few pages, you may wonder what the odds are that your child will be (or has been) diagnosed accurately. Or you may actually have gotten different labels for your child's difficulties, as Seth's and Chad's parents did, and want to know how to find out which one is right. Or perhaps you think the diagnosis you've gotten exaggerates or minimizes your child's problem. What do you do? When parents do not feel confident in the diagnosis their child has received, it is sometimes helpful to get a second or even a third opinion until what you're told makes sense in the context of how well you know your child and what you know about ASD. This is unfortunately a time-consuming and expensive process that many parents cannot afford. The following are our best, concise answers to questions that parents commonly raise about ASD diagnoses.

**What If One Professional Says My Child Has ASD and Another Says He's Normal?**

As we have emphasized throughout the first two chapters of this book, autistic-like behavior falls on a continuum. How often symptoms occur, how severe they are, how pervasive they are across []{#chapter02.html_page_37}different settings, how much they interfere with functioning, and how much distress they cause all factor into where your child falls on the spectrum and how close to what is considered "normal" he or she is. It's important to distinguish a diagnosis of ASD from the little quirks and eccentricities that we all have. Most symptoms of ASD can be found in some individuals without ASD, but usually in much milder form. You may well know someone who is obsessed with a topic---say, model trains or computers---but who in other ways seems perfectly typical and not at all autistic. A neighbor of mine (S. O.), who is absolutely normal in all other ways, checks a weather app on his phone a dozen times a day. He also enjoys keeping a list of when the sun rose and set in several cities around the world (usually places he and his wife have visited in their travels). Unlike people with ASD, however, he does not tell others about this interest and in fact was a bit embarrassed when I happened upon the list as I was looking for a pen at his house one day. Or you may know someone who seems at a loss for words and appears quite anxious in social situations. Or you may have acquaintances who ramble on in excruciating detail and never seem to get to the point. Or you may know people who are quite orderly and become anxious when plans change. A colleague of ours, who is a very friendly and social woman, likes to plan her entire day in advance. If someone calls an unplanned meeting or invites her to lunch on the spur of the moment, she becomes quite unsettled, avoids the change when possible, and otherwise complains heartily of the disruption in her day. Any of these folks could have ASD if, in addition to the one behavior described, they demonstrated other characteristic symptoms of ASD. However, each of these behavioral "quirks," when they occur in isolation and in the context of otherwise normal social relating and communication, are simply personality variants. What this means is that much of ASD is on a continuum with "normal" (we won't get into the debate about what "normal" actually means here). The behaviors of people with ASD are something that the rest of the non-ASD world might at times experience or that might feel "normal" to them. The difference, []{#chapter02.html_page_38}however, between someone who has ASD and someone who does not is the severity of the disturbance, in terms of both the number of autistic-like behaviors and how much these quirks interfere with functioning and daily living.

**How Can We Be Sure Our Child Has ASD and Not ADHD ... or OCD ... or Something Else?**

Estimates of the prevalence of ASD have soared during the past three decades. Although it is still unclear what has caused this rapid rise, as we discussed in [Chapter 1](#chapter01.html), one factor that has certainly contributed to it is that as professionals and the general public have become more familiar with ASD, the number of children diagnosed has soared. And as the diagnosis has become more prevalent, misdiagnosis is also more likely. Sometimes a proper assessment by a specialist reveals that this diagnosis is wrong and that the child's difficulties are more in the realm of attention problems, depression, or something other than ASD.

One reason for misdiagnosis is that the symptoms of certain disorders do have some overlap, at least superficially, with the symptoms of ASD. For example, obsessive--compulsive disorder (OCD) is a condition in which people have persistent thoughts or ideas that they have trouble getting out of their heads; they also feel extremely strong urges to perform certain behaviors or rituals. They often like to have things "just so" and become anxious or upset if things are not how they are used to or how they expect. Chris, a 12-year-old with OCD, had a favorite number (4) and felt compelled to perform actions and repeat certain phrases he had heard four times. If he didn't do this, he would become extremely nervous. The only way he could make his anxiety go away would be by making a quick sweeping motion on the floor with the back of his hand. Such unusual rituals may be somewhat reminiscent of the nonfunctional rituals of the autism spectrum. Take Mark, for example, a young boy with ASD who screams and cries if his family doesn't shut the doors of the car and fasten []{#chapter02.html_page_39}their seatbelts in a clockwise order, beginning with the driver. He insists that everyone get out of the car and repeat the process in the "right" order---and his family is willing to do this to avoid Mark's serious distress that otherwise results. Mark's rituals don't make any sense to others and don't seem to be functional in any way, just like Chris's rituals. Both boys experience tremendous anxiety when things aren't done just the way they want. Yet one boy is diagnosed with OCD and the other with ASD. What is the difference?

The answer is deceptively simple. If the car door rituals were Mark's only problem, he might well have OCD. But in combination with a variety of other difficulties, including avoiding eye contact, talking on and on about viruses, and showing no interest in friends, ASD is a much more complete diagnosis for Mark. A label of OCD would account for Mark's problems only partially. People with OCD do not have trouble socially interacting and are able to converse with others in a very natural way. Other than their obsessions and compulsions, they display few unusual behaviors; it is *not*, for example, a feature of OCD to have special, highly focused interests (although this is widely misunderstood and probably accounts for many misdiagnoses). What distinguishes ASD from all other conditions with which it might be confused are social reciprocity deficits and unusual communication style. If the hallmark symptoms of ASD are present, then the child most likely has ASD, not OCD or another condition.

How do professionals decide whether the child *also* has OCD? Many people with OCD recognize that their behavior is unusual and experience it as intrusive and senseless. The majority of people with OCD are quite secretive about their rituals, realizing that other people would consider them bizarre. Indeed, the affected people themselves find the rituals bizarre and fervently wish they would go away. But try as they might to suppress them, they cannot stop themselves from performing the behavior. This is quite different from the experience of most children or adolescents with ASD, who usually have little insight into the unusual nature of []{#chapter02.html_page_40}their behavior, do not consider it odd or eccentric, and make little attempt to conceal it. But not everyone with OCD has good insight into the unusual quality of their rituals; this is especially true of children. So a second important consideration in deciding whether a child has ASD alone or both ASD and OCD is the desire to achieve simplicity in diagnosis. During training, most professionals are encouraged to use the fewest diagnoses possible for one individual. When reasonable, we try to summarize difficulties under one diagnosis rather than listing three or four separate conditions. This practice is sometimes referred to as the "law of parsimony" or "Occam's razor." William of Occam was an English philosopher of the 14th century who stated that it should be a goal of science to first attempt to explain unknown phenomena in the simplest manner. When applied to medical diagnostics, doctors often say, "When you hear hoof beats, think horses, not zebras." Following the law of parsimony, most clinicians would not diagnose ASD and OCD together unless the manifestations of both were clearly present and the difficulties could not be accounted for by just one of the conditions.

A number of other disorders intersect with ASD. In fact, OCD is not the most common misdiagnosis or partial diagnosis. Some children with ASD have received a previous diagnosis of attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). The hallmarks of this condition, as you may be aware of and as the label conveys, are difficulty paying attention and controlling behavior and activity level. A child with ADHD may not seem to listen when spoken to or follow directions, may be reluctant to engage in tasks that are boring or effortful, may be distracted easily, fidget, leave his or her seat when sitting is expected, have difficulty waiting his or her turn, interrupt others, and talk excessively.

The similarities to ASD are probably immediately obvious. Many children with ASD display every one of these problems, but often for very different reasons than the child with ADHD. The child with ASD may not seem to listen and may not follow []{#chapter02.html_page_41}directions because of social deficits and language processing problems. He may not understand the centrality and importance of the human voice and may not orient to it naturally. Similarly, he may interrupt others, have trouble taking turns, and talk too much because of his difficulty reading social situations and knowing what is acceptable behavior in specific situations. He may be reluctant to do certain school assignments or have trouble staying seated, but not because these are inherently difficult tasks; they simply hold no interest for him. Praise from teachers or parents and high grades may not be incentives for the child with ASD, who has a vastly different motivation and reinforcement system than that of the typical child. He may be distracted, but not usually by the noises and other goings-on that distract the child with ADHD: the child with ASD is distracted by his own internal world, thoughts, and interests.

So one reason that children are often first diagnosed with ADHD, when in fact they have ASD, is that there is some overlap between the symptoms of the two conditions. A second reason is that ADHD is a common disorder, and thus clinicians are often more aware of it and better trained in its diagnosis than in diagnosis of ASD. Finally, the problems of ADHD (such as not remaining seated, not waiting turns, and not following directions) may be more bothersome to teachers and parents and thus may be brought to the attention of professionals more often than social awkwardness or highly specialized interests.

But just like a child with OCD alone, the child with ADHD alone does not have the problems with eye contact, conversation, range of interests, and imagination that the child with ASD has. The same approach should be taken to distinguish ASD from ADHD and the other conditions listed in [Table 1](#chapter02.html_tab-1){#chapter02.html_tab1} and to rule out any other apparently overlapping diagnosis. If the characteristic difficulties of ASD are present, then the child has ASD. The child receives multiple diagnoses only if all criteria for another condition are met and those features *cannot be accounted for by the ASD []{#chapter02.html_page_42}diagnosis*. In [Table 1](#chapter02.html_tab-1), we have listed some conditions that are confused with ASD.

