The consequences of misdiagnosis can be serious. Obviously, it is important to know the true nature of your child's difficulties to understand her best, but accurate diagnosis is also critical to getting your child the most appropriate services. Certain treatments are designed specifically for ASD and offer the best possible outcome in adult life (more on this topic in [Chapter 4](#chapter04.html)). An accurate diagnosis is essential to obtaining such resources. The correct diagnosis will also steer you away from interventions that will do no good and that might even harm your child, such as medications with serious side effects and behavioral treatments that focus on the wrong issues or make incorrect assumptions about the reasons why your child acts in the ways she does.

**Is It Possible That My Child Has Something Else in Addition to ASD?**

Although we strive to achieve simplicity in diagnosis, it is not always possible or accurate to diagnose a child with ASD alone. Having multiple psychiatric conditions is called "comorbidity," which is very important to detect, because if the other problems are left untreated, they can lead to an overall worsening in your child's functioning. Research has repeatedly shown that individuals with ASD are at higher risk than other individuals for the conditions listed in [Table 2](#chapter02.html_tab-2){#chapter02.html_tab2}, for reasons not fully understood yet. Several studies have shown that over half of children and adults with autism spectrum disorder have one or more of these comorbid conditions.

